title: Offload the actual setting commands onto a thread pool
message:
Offload the actual setting commands onto a thread pool

Use a countdown latch to actuall wait for the full job to complete

Ths is done because in the case of root toggles (Data, Airplane, Doze) it may take upwards
of 10 seconds for the full command to complete. While this will not hang the UI, it will
stop any of the other commands from running.

For example, if Wifi waits for Data which waits for Airplane to run, the possible delay between
Wifi actually running may be upwards of 15 seconds.

By threading the commands, all modifiers run in parallel, and the job simply waits for the longest
one to complete using a Countdown latch.

We also don't check for actual SU permission because the command will silent fail anyway, and
SU permission will be granted if the commands actually run

title: Special logic for Doze and Airplane mode
message:
Special logic for Doze and Airplane mode

Doze and Airplane mode are different from the usual job/manager interface

Normally, the manager turns off the device function if it is on when the screen is off,
and turns it on when the screen is on.

Airplane and Doze are different, they are turned ON when the screen is off, and OFF when
the screen is on. Because of this, they need custom jobs to implement this logic

In the custom job logic, called a ToggleJob instead of a ManageJob, the enable
will actually call the ManageJob.interalDisable(), and vice versa for disable.

Similarly, the managerInteractor will report the opposite of the enabled
state when queiried for a toggle job interface

title: Super kludge together the power trigger handling
message:
Super kludge together the power trigger handling

Power triggers will only be handled while the device is discharging
During a discharge, all the triggers are checked for their enabled state and availability
If they pass both, they are given a chance as the best trigger
Once all triggers are parsed, the best option is selected that meets all requirements
That trigger is marked unavailable and then run.

During a charge, all triggers below the current trigger are marked available for the next discharge

title: Create the backend managers
message:
Create the backend managers

The managers are powered by a lib which leverages the JobScheduler API or the
GMS included scheduler to perform device radio toggling.

The job scheduler handles multiple job queues, and is reliable to only run an event once.
It makes running jobs in parallel easy, and does not rely on manual threading.

While the inclusion of GCM requires the Internet permission, Power Manager itself does not
access the network in any direct way. The only network access performed would be from the JobManager,
which has the ability to check for network connections
